{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HrqhdD31fGsjrU6yAiWYXe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Implementation Checklist\n     2→- [ ] 1. Trace the current shared-helpers usage in cargo/npm/terra scripts and map each exact removal candidate to the corresponding `lib/x-agent-common.sh` export.\n     3→- [ ] 2. Capture a baseline expectation of current output behavior from `tests/run-scenarios.sh` (especially `Step`, `Result`, `Fix`, `Overall`, and lock-wait lines) before code edits.\n     4→- [ ] 3. Add `SCRIPT_DIR`/`LIB_DIR` resolution and `source \"${LIB_DIR}/x-agent-common.sh\"` immediately after `set -euo pipefail` in `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh`.\n     5→- [ ] 4. Remove from `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` all duplicated boilerplate: `KEEP_DIR`, `MAX_LINES`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT` defaults, `need`, `hr`, `step`, `fmt_elapsed`, `should_continue`, cleanup trap, and inline lock block.\n     6→- [ ] 5. Replace `cargo-agent` setup invocations with `setup_outdir \"cargo-agent\"` and `setup_lock \"cargo-agent\"`, preserving command ordering and lock timing side effects.\n     7→- [ ] 6. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and retaining npm-specific helpers and commands.\n     8→- [ ] 7. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and preserving terraform command flow.\n     9→- [ ] 8. Where any script currently prints final `Overall`/`Logs`, replace only the common final block with `print_overall \"$overall_ok\"` (if equivalent behavior is preserved).\n    10→- [ ] 9. Revalidate step sequencing for each agent so `RUN_<STEP>` logic, `--fail-fast`, and `help` path still behave identically after helper refactor.\n    11→- [ ] 10. Run targeted checks: `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`, and focused shellcheck on the three edited scripts.\n    12→- [ ] 11. Verify measurable file size reduction versus pre-edit baselines and confirm no helper behavior regressions from `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` (especially lock contention and cleanup semantics).\n    13→- [ ] 12. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n    14→- [ ] 13. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n    15→\n    16→## Architecture Review\n    17→\n    18→### System Boundaries\n    19→\n    20→The runtime is split into three layers.\n    21→\n    22→1) Shared runtime layer in `lib/x-agent-common.sh` holds boilerplate that is structurally identical across agents: output helpers, environment defaults, tool checks, output-dir lifecycle, lock lifecycle, and final summary formatting.\n    23→\n    24→2) Domain runner layer in `skills/<agent>/scripts/<agent>-agent.sh` holds project-specific logic only: command dispatch, tool arguments, package/tool-specific step functions, and domain-specific error messaging.\n    25→\n    26→3) Test/packaging layer in `tests/run-scenarios.sh` and `install.sh` exercises contract and distribution.\n    27→\n    28→`tests/run-scenarios.sh` is a strict integration boundary because all behavior claims are verified by the fixture contract, not by unit tests.\n    29→\n    30→### Dependency Graph and Coupling\n    31→\n    32→- Hard dependency: each edited script depends on `lib/x-agent-common.sh` at runtime.\n    33→- Direct coupling path: `SCRIPT_DIR -> ../../../lib -> lib/x-agent-common.sh` (fragile if scripts are relocated).\n    34→- Shared optional dependencies: `flock`, `perl`, `bash`, and command-line tools per agent.\n    35→- Packaging coupling: `install.sh` must ensure `lib/` is installed in both local and remote modes.\n    36→\n    37→The explicit coupling is acceptable for this phase but should be tracked because path-coupling is the highest single fragility point.\n    38→\n    39→### Data Flow Patterns and Bottlenecks\n    40→\n    41→1) Input/env processing: args and knobs are resolved first (`RUN_*`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `MAX_LINES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`).\n    42→2) Setup phase: create `OUTDIR`, install exit trap via `setup_outdir`, acquire lock via `setup_lock`.\n    43→3) Execution phase: run ordered steps, each writing command output to `$OUTDIR/<step>.log` and printing truncated diagnostics + elapsed time.\n    44→4) Aggregation: update `overall_ok`, optionally short-circuit with `should_continue`.\n    45→5) Summary phase: call `print_overall \"$overall_ok\"`, then return exit code.\n    46→\n    47→Primary bottlenecks remain external tool execution (`cargo`, `node`, `terraform`), not shell orchestration.\n    48→\n    49→### Security Architecture\n    50→\n    51→- Input vectors are local shell arguments and environment variables.\n    52→- Risk surface is command execution from user workspace; current pattern is command-injection-prone only if shell variables are interpolated unsafely. Existing scripts already pass this through unquoted args in places requiring shell parsing, so security posture is mostly inherited and must remain unchanged.\n    53→- Lock files are local and only advisory. Existing fallback to perl ensures compatibility but does not provide cryptographic guarantees.\n    54→- `install.sh` path rewriting and symlink/copy behavior should remain unchanged to avoid path injection from remote fetches; this phase only inherits those mechanics.\n    55→\n    56→### Architectural Decision Options\n    57→\n    58→1) Option A: Keep only hardcoded source path `../../../lib` and no abstraction.\n    59→Why: aligns with FR-2 requirement text and current install layout. Lowest code churn.\n    60→Cost/Risk: tight coupling to script location and difficult future portability.\n    61→Impact: fastest path, minimal change footprint.\n    62→\n    63→2) Option B: Introduce `resolve_lib_dir()` in `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\n    64→Why: centralizes path logic and reduces relocation risk.\n    65→Cost/Risk: deviates from explicit required snippet, may require additional behavior changes and tests now.\n    66→Impact: better future flexibility, higher refactor risk for this phase.\n    67→\n    68→3) Option C: Add per-agent `LIB_DIR` override env fallback (e.g., `RA_LAUNCHER_LIB_DIR`).\n    69→Why: allows tests or installs to override without path math in scripts.\n    70→Cost/Risk: extra configuration surface and allowed-tools complexity.\n    71→Impact: flexibility increase, but overkill for this narrow spec.\n    72→\n    73→Recommended: Option A for this phase because it matches explicit spec requirement and previous extraction assumptions, with a follow-up ticket for optional Option B once all agents are stable.\n    74→\n    75→### Implications for Future Specs\n    76→\n    77→- All future agent work should preserve helper boundary and call pattern for consistency.\n    78→- Future specs can de-duplicate path coupling by upgrading the shared lib to Option B after this phase.\n    79→- Any new agent should be validated against the same `run-scenarios` contract before introducing more helpers in the shared layer.\n    80→\n    81→## Code Quality Planning\n    82→\n    83→### Module Organization\n    84→\n    85→The goal is a clean separation between shared runtime helpers and domain step implementations.\n    86→\n    87→1. Keep `lib/x-agent-common.sh` as a pure helper module with no side effects on source.\n    88→2. Keep agent scripts minimal and domain-centric: parser, run_* functions, and dispatch only.\n    89→3. Keep all `CHANGE` behaviors (`CHANGED_FILES`) in domain scripts because semantics differ by tool.\n    90→\n    91→### DRY Opportunities\n    92→\n    93→Most duplication is exactly the boilerplate block, not business logic.\n    94→\n    95→- Remove repeated block variables and helper functions from all three scripts.\n    96→- Reuse `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` exactly once in each script.\n    97→- Keep helper calls like `print_overall` only where identical to avoid introducing non-equivalent wrappers.\n    98→\n    99→### Error Handling Patterns to Preserve\n   100→\n   101→- `need` must continue to exit 2 for missing required tooling.\n   102→- `cleanup` semantics must remain: preserve `$OUTDIR` on failure or `KEEP_DIR=1`, remove on success otherwise.\n   103→- Help path (`help`, `--help`, `-h`) must still run without project preconditions.\n   104→- Lock wait message must still print when lock contention exists.\n   105→- `overall_ok` must preserve step-level fail state.\n   106→\n   107→### Explicit Edge Cases to Handle\n   108→\n   109→- If script receives unknown command: exit 2 and usage message.\n   110→- If required tool missing: immediate 2 with same message shape.\n   111→- If lock mechanism unavailable and neither flock nor perl present: warning with continuation.\n   112→- If running under CI (`CI=true|1`): `MAX_LINES` unlimited and check-only behavior unaffected.\n   113→- If `RUN_*` is set to 0: skip step exactly as before.\n   114→- If `FAIL_FAST=1`: stop after first failure in multi-step mode.\n   115→- If `KEEP_DIR=1`: trap must preserve path and exit still returns original status.\n   116→\n   117→### Technical Debt Prevention\n   118→\n   119→- Keep source block order strict and canonical to minimize later merges.\n   120→- Avoid in-script partial duplication of print logic to reduce drift from shared library contract.\n   121→- Do not alter command argument handling for existing agent features; only move boilerplate.\n   122→- Preserve line-level output where feasible, because this is a behavioral contract and tested by snapshots.\n   123→\n   124→### Engineering Level\n   125→\n   126→Use minimal-variance refactoring. Move boilerplate only, preserve command ordering and output contracts, and avoid introducing generic abstractions beyond what this spec requires.\n   127→\n   128→## Test Strategy\n   129→\n   130→### Unit-level checks\n   131→\n   132→Use direct script-level invocations where available to validate helper contracts after refactor.\n   133→\n   134→- Source and run small sanity checks for `set -euo` handling and `help` invocation path behavior for each edited script.\n   135→- Confirm lock fallback still executes when `flock` is missing by simulating missing command paths in an isolated environment if feasible.\n   136→- Confirm `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` invocation points are identical in all `main` paths.\n   137→\n   138→### Integration checks\n   139→\n   140→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`\n   141→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`\n   142→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`\n   143→- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh`\n   144→- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh`\n   145→- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh`\n   146→- `tests/run-scenarios.sh shellcheck`\n   147→\n   148→### End-to-end and output-parity checks\n   149→\n   150→- Run all three scenario suites and ensure exit codes still match expected clean/issues outcomes.\n   151→- Capture baseline outputs for `clean`, `issues`, `help`, and lock fixtures before changes (if no baseline files exist, create temporary local baseline in work folder).\n   152→- Re-run and diff outputs after refactor with `Time:` line normalization so only timing drift is accepted.\n   153→- Confirm `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` still prints wait message and exits successfully.\n   154→\n   155→### Failure modes and error paths\n   156→\n   157→- Missing required tools in scenario should continue to `SKIP` when declared in scenario file and still pass the suite.\n   158→- Missing optional tools must still produce valid `SKIP` step results for affected steps.\n   159→- Unknown commands and missing required project files must still return code 2.\n   160→- Lock contention and lockfile cleanup should behave identically to avoid flaky CI.\n   161→\n   162→### Assertion strength expectations\n   163→\n   164→Assertions should be status-based plus specific output line checks (`Overall: PASS|FAIL`, `Result: PASS|FAIL`, `Fix:` when failing, lock waiting message, and cleanup behavior). Scenario-based tests should remain the primary oracle because they encode real command flows.\n   165→\n   166→## Performance Considerations\n   167→\n   168→### N+1 and heavy access patterns\n   169→\n   170→- Avoid adding repeated `cargo metadata` calls; keep current one-time/conditional invocation patterns.\n   171→- Keep `CHANGED_FILES` scanning and log directory creation per-agent unchanged to avoid additional process overhead.\n   172→- Avoid introducing extra `cat`/`grep` passes over large files in step routines.\n   173→\n   174→### Memory usage\n   175→\n   176→- Shared helper calls are lightweight and do not introduce persistent large data structures.\n   177→- `terraform` and `cargo` outputs remain on disk in log files as before; no in-memory buffering explosion risk.\n   178→\n   179→### Caching opportunities\n   180→\n   181→- Existing cargo helper already caches metadata in `_WS_PACKAGES` and similar variables. Preserve this as-is.\n   182→- Avoid clearing/transforming shared cached variables from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` so agent-level caches remain local.\n   183→\n   184→### Slow paths and optimization points\n   185→\n   186→- Lock contention path is intentionally blocking by design to preserve correctness under concurrent runs.\n   187→- CLI argument parsing and env resolution are constant time.\n   188→- Biggest runtime cost is external commands; no additional slow shell loops should be added.\n   189→\n   190→## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n   191→\n   192→1. What: Create a precise refactor inventory and confirm pre-change behavior boundaries.\n   193→Why: this avoids accidental changes and lets us compare output parity.\n   194→How: review the three target scripts and mark each occurrence of duplicated block functions/variables, lock setup, cleanup trap, and final output block.\n   195→Edge Cases: avoid misclassifying domain logic as boilerplate, especially cargo’s SQLX skip/error hints.\n   196→Tests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh <agent>` on current branch and store output snapshots for critical commands.\n   197→Risks: insufficient inventory can cause missed duplicate deletion or broken argument handling.\n   198→\n   199→2. What: Edit `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove duplicated boilerplate.\n   200→Why: this script has the highest complexity and highest regression risk, so it should be stabilized first.\n   201→How: add source block after `set -euo pipefail`, then remove exactly the shared variable/dependency/setup/lock/format helpers while keeping all step functions untouched.\n   202→Edge Cases: preserve `JQ_BIN` handling, export behavior for `SQLX_OFFLINE`, and all path-sensitive log names.\n   203→Tests: run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`.\n   204→Risks: helper replacement may alter output if final-print behavior is changed inappropriately.\n   205→\n   206→3. What: Edit `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove boilerplate.\n   207→Why: npm has array-based scoping behavior and package-manager detection that must stay unchanged.\n   208→How: insert shared source block, remove duplicate variable and helper code, and replace setup/lock setup calls with `setup_outdir \"npm-agent\"` and `setup_lock \"npm-agent\"`.\n   209→Edge Cases: keep `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, `PM` detection, and step commands (`npm run`) unchanged.\n   210→Tests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent` and check `npm-agent --help` still prints usage without requiring project context.\n   211→Risks: helper replacement could inadvertently move `PM` detection outside of lock/setup ordering or break command scope assumptions.\n   212→\n   213→4. What: Edit `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove boilerplate.\n   214→Why: terraform steps are highly sensitive to context changes; refactor must not alter command wrappers.\n   215→How: apply the same source + replacement pattern as other scripts and retain terraform-specific `tf()` behavior and `TERRAFORM_CHDIR` resolution logic.\n   216→Edge Cases: preserve `tflint` optional-skip behavior and plan-safe output path expectations.\n   217→Tests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent` and `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` only for lock behavior reference.\n   218→Risks: lock and output-dir interactions can interfere with Terraform command wrappers if call sites are moved.\n   219→\n   220→5. What: Replace final summary output blocks with `print_overall` where appropriate.\n   221→Why: reduces duplicated contract surface and aligns scripts with shared library contract.\n   222→How: replace only equivalent final block forms and ensure `print_overall` receives `overall_ok` with no extra formatting around it.\n   223→Edge Cases: do not remove custom command-specific status lines or extra logs that appear before final summary.\n   224→Tests: run each agent in `help` and `all` paths and assert `Overall:` and `Logs:` formatting remains present.\n   225→Risks: one-off summary differences may be interpreted as output drift.\n   226→\n   227→6. What: Verify concurrency path and lock behavior remain byte-for-byte equivalent.\n   228→Why: lock behavior is explicitly validated via fixture and is easy to regress.\n   229→How: run `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` before and after refactor; compare message timing and completion behavior.\n   230→Edge Cases: lock tool availability variation (`flock` vs `perl`) must remain covered via runtime fallback logic.\n   231→Tests: run `bash tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` (through scenario runner or direct execution as fixture defines).\n   232→Risks: changing lock acquisition order relative to setup can silently break wait messaging.\n   233→\n   234→7. What: Implement an output-parity capture check excluding allowed `Time:` variance.\n   235→Why: spec requires byte-identical output except timing, and scenario runner only checks exit status.\n   236→How: build a local diff helper that normalizes `Time: <number>s` from outputs and compares pre/post refactor captures for the three agents.\n   237→Edge Cases: lock wait lines and path-sensitive values may vary with run context, so normalize only timing lines and ignore nondeterministic temp paths if needed.\n   238→Tests: run parity check on `help`, `clean`, and `issues` commands for each agent.\n   239→Risks: over-normalization can hide real regressions; keep normalization strict.\n   240→\n   241→8. What: Validate script line-count reduction and maintain a measured delta.\n   242→Why: this is a direct acceptance target and helps confirm boilerplate removal.\n   243→How: run `wc -l` on each edited script and compare with pre-refactor baselines.\n   244→Edge Cases: baseline should be captured before edits; do not normalize generated temporary files.\n   245→Tests: assert resulting file sizes are lower than baseline; if not, review accidental reinsertion of duplicated helpers.\n   246→Risks: large in-script formatting adjustments can mask lack of real removal; focus on logical duplication removal.\n   247→\n   248→9. What: Run strict scenario gates with explicit filters and tool-specific variants.\n   249→Why: CI-equivalent validation reduces surprise before final submission.\n   250→How: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`, and optionally `tests/run-scenarios.sh` full in final pass.\n   251→Edge Cases: optional-tool scenarios must still be skipped or passed depending on environment.\n   252→Tests: verify all scenario exit codes and printed labels are unchanged.\n   253→Risks: environment differences (local tools) could alter skip behavior and produce false negatives.\n   254→\n   255→10. What: Re-check installation and docs assumptions for this spec boundary.\n   256→Why: source-path assumptions already depend on `install.sh` behavior from previous extraction.\n   257→How: confirm no changes needed for this spec, but verify running a checked-out install path can still resolve `../../../lib` from all three scripts.\n   258→Edge Cases: remote/local path structures should remain unchanged.\n   259→Tests: quick smoke command: run each script once from expected install location with local checkout and `CI=true`.\n   260→Risks: script path expectations can drift if someone already moved agent directories.\n   261→\n   262→11. What: Update `.ralph/exploration.md` after implementation if observed implementation details changed.\n   263→Why: this keeps future agents from rediscovering unchanged coupling and command flow.\n   264→How: add/update `Key Files & Roles`, `Dependency and coupling notes`, and test fixture notes if any new patterns emerged.\n   265→Edge Cases: avoid documenting assumptions that depend on ephemeral local environment.\n   266→Tests: manual consistency review only; keep concise and oriented to implementation.\n   267→Risks: stale or contradictory exploration notes can increase future discovery cost.\n   268→\n   269→12. What: Finalize execution acceptance.\n   270→Why: the phase is only complete when all acceptance checks pass and are validated by the agent loop.\n   271→How: run `ralph validate work`, then keep a final note of outcomes and any follow-up risks.\n   272→Edge Cases: if `ralph validate work` fails, return to step 2 or step 6 based on reported blockers.\n   273→Tests: `ralph validate work` must report PASS.\n   274→Risks: one failed gate requires iterative rerun after targeted fix.\n   275→\n   276→## Decision Log\n   277→\n   278→### Decision: Use shared setup helpers or retain per-agent setup code\n   279→- Decision: Use `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` across all three scripts.\n   280→- Options Considered: retain each agent's existing setup logic; add partially shared wrappers while preserving original helpers; full shared helper adoption.\n   281→- Chosen Approach: Full adoption of shared helpers because this directly validates FR-1 and reduces drift.\n   282→- Implications: simpler scripts, reduced duplicated lifecycle logic, but requires stronger parity checks for output and lock timing.\n   283→\n   284→### Decision: Keep source path pattern as mandated snippet\n   285→- Decision: Use `SCRIPT_DIR` + `LIB_DIR=\"${SCRIPT_DIR}/../../../lib\"` exactly as documented.\n   286→- Options Considered: absolute path detection, fallback env override, `resolve_lib_dir()`.\n   287→- Chosen Approach: mandated hardcoded relative path for this phase.\n   288→- Implications: fast and compliant with the spec contract; leaves explicit coupling to script layout.\n   289→\n   290→### Decision: Replace common final summary block with shared printer\n   291→- Decision: Replace only equivalent final summary output with `print_overall`.\n   292→- Options Considered: keep all final blocks inline; partial extraction with `print_result` only; full shared finalization.\n   293→- Chosen Approach: use shared `print_overall` where behavior matches exactly.\n   294→- Implications: less output duplication and consistent overall output, with explicit parity diff to guard accidental formatting drift.\n   295→\n   296→## Edge Cases and Risks\n   297→\n   298→- Output parity drift is possible in timing and trailing blank-line handling. Mitigation: normalized-diff comparison before final acceptance.\n   299→- Lock path behavior can drift if setup order changes. Mitigation: run flock test fixture and compare message sequence.\n   300→- `help` command must remain fast and independent of project root validation. Mitigation: keep early usage handling in each main function.\n   301→- Optional tool absence can become false failures. Mitigation: scenario-required tools gating should remain unchanged and no new unconditional checks should be introduced.\n   302→- Sourcing shared library without side effects must be preserved. Mitigation: no extra output in source phase; no additional initialization on source.\n   303→- Path coupling risk if repo structure changes later. Mitigation: log as known coupling in exploration and architecture notes, then plan optional `resolve_lib_dir` follow-up.\n   304→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6009da08-f492-4e44-8ec1-e3891bd2efc5","uuid":"56f1266c-c578-4115-83bb-60386f8b8a0e","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/work-plan.txt","content":"## Implementation Checklist\n- [ ] 1. Trace the current shared-helpers usage in cargo/npm/terra scripts and map each exact removal candidate to the corresponding `lib/x-agent-common.sh` export.\n- [ ] 2. Capture a baseline expectation of current output behavior from `tests/run-scenarios.sh` (especially `Step`, `Result`, `Fix`, `Overall`, and lock-wait lines) before code edits.\n- [ ] 3. Add `SCRIPT_DIR`/`LIB_DIR` resolution and `source \"${LIB_DIR}/x-agent-common.sh\"` immediately after `set -euo pipefail` in `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh`.\n- [ ] 4. Remove from `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` all duplicated boilerplate: `KEEP_DIR`, `MAX_LINES`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT` defaults, `need`, `hr`, `step`, `fmt_elapsed`, `should_continue`, cleanup trap, and inline lock block.\n- [ ] 5. Replace `cargo-agent` setup invocations with `setup_outdir \"cargo-agent\"` and `setup_lock \"cargo-agent\"`, preserving command ordering and lock timing side effects.\n- [ ] 6. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and retaining npm-specific helpers and commands.\n- [ ] 7. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and preserving terraform command flow.\n- [ ] 8. Where any script currently prints final `Overall`/`Logs`, replace only the common final block with `print_overall \"$overall_ok\"` (if equivalent behavior is preserved).\n- [ ] 9. Revalidate step sequencing for each agent so `RUN_<STEP>` logic, `--fail-fast`, and `help` path still behave identically after helper refactor.\n- [ ] 10. Run targeted checks: `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`, and focused shellcheck on the three edited scripts.\n- [ ] 11. Verify measurable file size reduction versus pre-edit baselines and confirm no helper behavior regressions from `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` (especially lock contention and cleanup semantics).\n- [ ] 12. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n- [ ] 13. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n\n## Architecture Review\n\n### System Boundaries\n\nThe runtime is split into three layers.\n\n1) Shared runtime layer in `lib/x-agent-common.sh` holds boilerplate that is structurally identical across agents: output helpers, environment defaults, tool checks, output-dir lifecycle, lock lifecycle, and final summary formatting.\n\n2) Domain runner layer in `skills/<agent>/scripts/<agent>-agent.sh` holds project-specific logic only: command dispatch, tool arguments, package/tool-specific step functions, and domain-specific error messaging.\n\n3) Test/packaging layer in `tests/run-scenarios.sh` and `install.sh` exercises contract and distribution.\n\n`tests/run-scenarios.sh` is a strict integration boundary because all behavior claims are verified by the fixture contract, not by unit tests.\n\n### Dependency Graph and Coupling\n\n- Hard dependency: each edited script depends on `lib/x-agent-common.sh` at runtime.\n- Direct coupling path: `SCRIPT_DIR -> ../../../lib -> lib/x-agent-common.sh` (fragile if scripts are relocated).\n- Shared optional dependencies: `flock`, `perl`, `bash`, and command-line tools per agent.\n- Packaging coupling: `install.sh` must ensure `lib/` is installed in both local and remote modes.\n\nThe explicit coupling is acceptable for this phase but should be tracked because path-coupling is the highest single fragility point.\n\n### Data Flow Patterns and Bottlenecks\n\n1) Input/env processing: args and knobs are resolved first (`RUN_*`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `MAX_LINES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`).\n2) Setup phase: create `OUTDIR`, install exit trap via `setup_outdir`, acquire lock via `setup_lock`.\n3) Execution phase: run ordered steps, each writing command output to `$OUTDIR/<step>.log` and printing truncated diagnostics + elapsed time.\n4) Aggregation: update `overall_ok`, optionally short-circuit with `should_continue`.\n5) Summary phase: call `print_overall \"$overall_ok\"`, then return exit code.\n\nPrimary bottlenecks remain external tool execution (`cargo`, `node`, `terraform`), not shell orchestration.\n\n### Security Architecture\n\n- Input vectors are local shell arguments and environment variables.\n- Risk surface is command execution from user workspace; current pattern is command-injection-prone only if shell variables are interpolated unsafely. Existing scripts already pass this through unquoted args in places requiring shell parsing, so security posture is mostly inherited and must remain unchanged.\n- Lock files are local and only advisory. Existing fallback to perl ensures compatibility but does not provide cryptographic guarantees.\n- `install.sh` path rewriting and symlink/copy behavior should remain unchanged to avoid path injection from remote fetches; this phase only inherits those mechanics.\n\n### Architectural Decision Options\n\n1) Option A: Keep only hardcoded source path `../../../lib` and no abstraction.\nWhy: aligns with FR-2 requirement text and current install layout. Lowest code churn.\nCost/Risk: tight coupling to script location and difficult future portability.\nImpact: fastest path, minimal change footprint.\n\n2) Option B: Introduce `resolve_lib_dir()` in `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\nWhy: centralizes path logic and reduces relocation risk.\nCost/Risk: deviates from explicit required snippet, may require additional behavior changes and tests now.\nImpact: better future flexibility, higher refactor risk for this phase.\n\n3) Option C: Add per-agent `LIB_DIR` override env fallback (e.g., `RA_LAUNCHER_LIB_DIR`).\nWhy: allows tests or installs to override without path math in scripts.\nCost/Risk: extra configuration surface and allowed-tools complexity.\nImpact: flexibility increase, but overkill for this narrow spec.\n\nRecommended: Option A for this phase because it matches explicit spec requirement and previous extraction assumptions, with a follow-up ticket for optional Option B once all agents are stable.\n\n### Implications for Future Specs\n\n- All future agent work should preserve helper boundary and call pattern for consistency.\n- Future specs can de-duplicate path coupling by upgrading the shared lib to Option B after this phase.\n- Any new agent should be validated against the same `run-scenarios` contract before introducing more helpers in the shared layer.\n\n## Code Quality Planning\n\n### Module Organization\n\nThe goal is a clean separation between shared runtime helpers and domain step implementations.\n\n1. Keep `lib/x-agent-common.sh` as a pure helper module with no side effects on source.\n2. Keep agent scripts minimal and domain-centric: parser, run_* functions, and dispatch only.\n3. Keep all `CHANGE` behaviors (`CHANGED_FILES`) in domain scripts because semantics differ by tool.\n\n### DRY Opportunities\n\nMost duplication is exactly the boilerplate block, not business logic.\n\n- Remove repeated block variables and helper functions from all three scripts.\n- Reuse `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` exactly once in each script.\n- Keep helper calls like `print_overall` only where identical to avoid introducing non-equivalent wrappers.\n\n### Error Handling Patterns to Preserve\n\n- `need` must continue to exit 2 for missing required tooling.\n- `cleanup` semantics must remain: preserve `$OUTDIR` on failure or `KEEP_DIR=1`, remove on success otherwise.\n- Help path (`help`, `--help`, `-h`) must still run without project preconditions.\n- Lock wait message must still print when lock contention exists.\n- `overall_ok` must preserve step-level fail state.\n\n### Explicit Edge Cases to Handle\n\n- If script receives unknown command: exit 2 and usage message.\n- If required tool missing: immediate 2 with same message shape.\n- If lock mechanism unavailable and neither flock nor perl present: warning with continuation.\n- If running under CI (`CI=true|1`): `MAX_LINES` unlimited and check-only behavior unaffected.\n- If `RUN_*` is set to 0: skip step exactly as before.\n- If `FAIL_FAST=1`: stop after first failure in multi-step mode.\n- If `KEEP_DIR=1`: trap must preserve path and exit still returns original status.\n\n### Technical Debt Prevention\n\n- Keep source block order strict and canonical to minimize later merges.\n- Avoid in-script partial duplication of print logic to reduce drift from shared library contract.\n- Do not alter command argument handling for existing agent features; only move boilerplate.\n- Preserve line-level output where feasible, because this is a behavioral contract and tested by snapshots.\n\n### Engineering Level\n\nUse minimal-variance refactoring. Move boilerplate only, preserve command ordering and output contracts, and avoid introducing generic abstractions beyond what this spec requires.\n\n## Test Strategy\n\n### Unit-level checks\n\nUse direct script-level invocations where available to validate helper contracts after refactor.\n\n- Source and run small sanity checks for `set -euo` handling and `help` invocation path behavior for each edited script.\n- Confirm lock fallback still executes when `flock` is missing by simulating missing command paths in an isolated environment if feasible.\n- Confirm `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` invocation points are identical in all `main` paths.\n\n### Integration checks\n\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`\n- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh`\n- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh`\n- `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh`\n- `tests/run-scenarios.sh shellcheck`\n\n### End-to-end and output-parity checks\n\n- Run all three scenario suites and ensure exit codes still match expected clean/issues outcomes.\n- Capture baseline outputs for `clean`, `issues`, `help`, and lock fixtures before changes (if no baseline files exist, create temporary local baseline in work folder).\n- Re-run and diff outputs after refactor with `Time:` line normalization so only timing drift is accepted.\n- Confirm `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` still prints wait message and exits successfully.\n\n### Failure modes and error paths\n\n- Missing required tools in scenario should continue to `SKIP` when declared in scenario file and still pass the suite.\n- Missing optional tools must still produce valid `SKIP` step results for affected steps.\n- Unknown commands and missing required project files must still return code 2.\n- Lock contention and lockfile cleanup should behave identically to avoid flaky CI.\n\n### Assertion strength expectations\n\nAssertions should be status-based plus specific output line checks (`Overall: PASS|FAIL`, `Result: PASS|FAIL`, `Fix:` when failing, lock waiting message, and cleanup behavior). Scenario-based tests should remain the primary oracle because they encode real command flows.\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n### N+1 and heavy access patterns\n\n- Avoid adding repeated `cargo metadata` calls; keep current one-time/conditional invocation patterns.\n- Keep `CHANGED_FILES` scanning and log directory creation per-agent unchanged to avoid additional process overhead.\n- Avoid introducing extra `cat`/`grep` passes over large files in step routines.\n\n### Memory usage\n\n- Shared helper calls are lightweight and do not introduce persistent large data structures.\n- `terraform` and `cargo` outputs remain on disk in log files as before; no in-memory buffering explosion risk.\n\n### Caching opportunities\n\n- Existing cargo helper already caches metadata in `_WS_PACKAGES` and similar variables. Preserve this as-is.\n- Avoid clearing/transforming shared cached variables from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` so agent-level caches remain local.\n\n### Slow paths and optimization points\n\n- Lock contention path is intentionally blocking by design to preserve correctness under concurrent runs.\n- CLI argument parsing and env resolution are constant time.\n- Biggest runtime cost is external commands; no additional slow shell loops should be added.\n\n## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n\n1. What: Create a precise refactor inventory and confirm pre-change behavior boundaries.\nWhy: this avoids accidental changes and lets us compare output parity.\nHow: review the three target scripts and mark each occurrence of duplicated block functions/variables, lock setup, cleanup trap, and final output block.\nEdge Cases: avoid misclassifying domain logic as boilerplate, especially cargo’s SQLX skip/error hints.\nTests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh <agent>` on current branch and store output snapshots for critical commands.\nRisks: insufficient inventory can cause missed duplicate deletion or broken argument handling.\n\n2. What: Edit `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove duplicated boilerplate.\nWhy: this script has the highest complexity and highest regression risk, so it should be stabilized first.\nHow: add source block after `set -euo pipefail`, then remove exactly the shared variable/dependency/setup/lock/format helpers while keeping all step functions untouched.\nEdge Cases: preserve `JQ_BIN` handling, export behavior for `SQLX_OFFLINE`, and all path-sensitive log names.\nTests: run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`.\nRisks: helper replacement may alter output if final-print behavior is changed inappropriately.\n\n3. What: Edit `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove boilerplate.\nWhy: npm has array-based scoping behavior and package-manager detection that must stay unchanged.\nHow: insert shared source block, remove duplicate variable and helper code, and replace setup/lock setup calls with `setup_outdir \"npm-agent\"` and `setup_lock \"npm-agent\"`.\nEdge Cases: keep `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, `PM` detection, and step commands (`npm run`) unchanged.\nTests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent` and check `npm-agent --help` still prints usage without requiring project context.\nRisks: helper replacement could inadvertently move `PM` detection outside of lock/setup ordering or break command scope assumptions.\n\n4. What: Edit `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` to source shared helpers and remove boilerplate.\nWhy: terraform steps are highly sensitive to context changes; refactor must not alter command wrappers.\nHow: apply the same source + replacement pattern as other scripts and retain terraform-specific `tf()` behavior and `TERRAFORM_CHDIR` resolution logic.\nEdge Cases: preserve `tflint` optional-skip behavior and plan-safe output path expectations.\nTests: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent` and `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` only for lock behavior reference.\nRisks: lock and output-dir interactions can interfere with Terraform command wrappers if call sites are moved.\n\n5. What: Replace final summary output blocks with `print_overall` where appropriate.\nWhy: reduces duplicated contract surface and aligns scripts with shared library contract.\nHow: replace only equivalent final block forms and ensure `print_overall` receives `overall_ok` with no extra formatting around it.\nEdge Cases: do not remove custom command-specific status lines or extra logs that appear before final summary.\nTests: run each agent in `help` and `all` paths and assert `Overall:` and `Logs:` formatting remains present.\nRisks: one-off summary differences may be interpreted as output drift.\n\n6. What: Verify concurrency path and lock behavior remain byte-for-byte equivalent.\nWhy: lock behavior is explicitly validated via fixture and is easy to regress.\nHow: run `tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` before and after refactor; compare message timing and completion behavior.\nEdge Cases: lock tool availability variation (`flock` vs `perl`) must remain covered via runtime fallback logic.\nTests: run `bash tests/cargo-agent/flock/flock-test.sh` (through scenario runner or direct execution as fixture defines).\nRisks: changing lock acquisition order relative to setup can silently break wait messaging.\n\n7. What: Implement an output-parity capture check excluding allowed `Time:` variance.\nWhy: spec requires byte-identical output except timing, and scenario runner only checks exit status.\nHow: build a local diff helper that normalizes `Time: <number>s` from outputs and compares pre/post refactor captures for the three agents.\nEdge Cases: lock wait lines and path-sensitive values may vary with run context, so normalize only timing lines and ignore nondeterministic temp paths if needed.\nTests: run parity check on `help`, `clean`, and `issues` commands for each agent.\nRisks: over-normalization can hide real regressions; keep normalization strict.\n\n8. What: Validate script line-count reduction and maintain a measured delta.\nWhy: this is a direct acceptance target and helps confirm boilerplate removal.\nHow: run `wc -l` on each edited script and compare with pre-refactor baselines.\nEdge Cases: baseline should be captured before edits; do not normalize generated temporary files.\nTests: assert resulting file sizes are lower than baseline; if not, review accidental reinsertion of duplicated helpers.\nRisks: large in-script formatting adjustments can mask lack of real removal; focus on logical duplication removal.\n\n9. What: Run strict scenario gates with explicit filters and tool-specific variants.\nWhy: CI-equivalent validation reduces surprise before final submission.\nHow: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`, and optionally `tests/run-scenarios.sh` full in final pass.\nEdge Cases: optional-tool scenarios must still be skipped or passed depending on environment.\nTests: verify all scenario exit codes and printed labels are unchanged.\nRisks: environment differences (local tools) could alter skip behavior and produce false negatives.\n\n10. What: Re-check installation and docs assumptions for this spec boundary.\nWhy: source-path assumptions already depend on `install.sh` behavior from previous extraction.\nHow: confirm no changes needed for this spec, but verify running a checked-out install path can still resolve `../../../lib` from all three scripts.\nEdge Cases: remote/local path structures should remain unchanged.\nTests: quick smoke command: run each script once from expected install location with local checkout and `CI=true`.\nRisks: script path expectations can drift if someone already moved agent directories.\n\n11. What: Update `.ralph/exploration.md` after implementation if observed implementation details changed.\nWhy: this keeps future agents from rediscovering unchanged coupling and command flow.\nHow: add/update `Key Files & Roles`, `Dependency and coupling notes`, and test fixture notes if any new patterns emerged.\nEdge Cases: avoid documenting assumptions that depend on ephemeral local environment.\nTests: manual consistency review only; keep concise and oriented to implementation.\nRisks: stale or contradictory exploration notes can increase future discovery cost.\n\n12. What: Finalize execution acceptance.\nWhy: the phase is only complete when all acceptance checks pass and are validated by the agent loop.\nHow: run `ralph validate work`, then keep a final note of outcomes and any follow-up risks.\nEdge Cases: if `ralph validate work` fails, return to step 2 or step 6 based on reported blockers.\nTests: `ralph validate work` must report PASS.\nRisks: one failed gate requires iterative rerun after targeted fix.\n\n## Decision Log\n\n### Decision: Use shared setup helpers or retain per-agent setup code\n- Decision: Use `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` from `lib/x-agent-common.sh` across all three scripts.\n- Options Considered: retain each agent's existing setup logic; add partially shared wrappers while preserving original helpers; full shared helper adoption.\n- Chosen Approach: Full adoption of shared helpers because this directly validates FR-1 and reduces drift.\n- Implications: simpler scripts, reduced duplicated lifecycle logic, but requires stronger parity checks for output and lock timing.\n\n### Decision: Keep source path pattern as mandated snippet\n- Decision: Use `SCRIPT_DIR` + `LIB_DIR=\"${SCRIPT_DIR}/../../../lib\"` exactly as documented.\n- Options Considered: absolute path detection, fallback env override, `resolve_lib_dir()`.\n- Chosen Approach: mandated hardcoded relative path for this phase.\n- Implications: fast and compliant with the spec contract; leaves explicit coupling to script layout.\n\n### Decision: Replace common final summary block with shared printer\n- Decision: Replace only equivalent final summary output with `print_overall`.\n- Options Considered: keep all final blocks inline; partial extraction with `print_result` only; full shared finalization.\n- Chosen Approach: use shared `print_overall` where behavior matches exactly.\n- Implications: less output duplication and consistent overall output, with explicit parity diff to guard accidental formatting drift.\n\n## Edge Cases and Risks\n\n- Output parity drift is possible in timing and trailing blank-line handling. Mitigation: normalized-diff comparison before final acceptance.\n- Lock path behavior can drift if setup order changes. Mitigation: run flock test fixture and compare message sequence.\n- `help` command must remain fast and independent of project root validation. Mitigation: keep early usage handling in each main function.\n- Optional tool absence can become false failures. Mitigation: scenario-required tools gating should remain unchanged and no new unconditional checks should be introduced.\n- Sourcing shared library without side effects must be preserved. Mitigation: no extra output in source phase; no additional initialization on source.\n- Path coupling risk if repo structure changes later. Mitigation: log as known coupling in exploration and architecture notes, then plan optional `resolve_lib_dir` follow-up.\n","numLines":304,"startLine":1,"totalLines":304}}}
