nt.md\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\",\"numLines\":61,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":61}}}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01UJrJ9iUTHN176w4Mc1EXXW\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01HrqhdD31fGsjrU6yAiWYXe\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/work-plan.txt\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":17929,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":9280,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":17929},\"output_tokens\":10,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"parent_tool_use_id\":null,\"session_id\":\"6009da08-f492-4e44-8ec1-e3891bd2efc5\",\"uuid\":\"466e4e0d-0b76-406c-8bac-33e0290d779d\"}\n{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01HrqhdD31fGsjrU6yAiWYXe\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→## Implementation Checklist\\n     2→- [ ] 1. Trace the current shared-helpers usage in cargo/npm/terra scripts and map each exact removal candidate to the corresponding `lib/x-agent-common.sh` export.\\n     3→- [ ] 2. Capture a baseline expectation of current output behavior from `tests/run-scenarios.sh` (especially `Step`, `Result`, `Fix`, `Overall`, and lock-wait lines) before code edits.\\n     4→- [ ] 3. Add `SCRIPT_DIR`/`LIB_DIR` resolution and `source \\\"${LIB_DIR}/x-agent-common.sh\\\"` immediately after `set -euo pipefail` in `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh`.\\n     5→- [ ] 4. Remove from `skills/cargo-agent/scripts/cargo-agent.sh` all duplicated boilerplate: `KEEP_DIR`, `MAX_LINES`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT` defaults, `need`, `hr`, `step`, `fmt_elapsed`, `should_continue`, cleanup trap, and inline lock block.\\n     6→- [ ] 5. Replace `cargo-agent` setup invocations with `setup_outdir \\\"cargo-agent\\\"` and `setup_lock \\\"cargo-agent\\\"`, preserving command ordering and lock timing side effects.\\n     7→- [ ] 6. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/npm-agent/scripts/npm-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and retaining npm-specific helpers and commands.\\n     8→- [ ] 7. Add `source` lines and remove duplicated boilerplate in `skills/terra-agent/scripts/terra-agent.sh` using the same `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` pattern and preserving terraform command flow.\\n     9→- [ ] 8. Where any script currently prints final `Overall`/`Logs`, replace only the common final block with `print_overall \\\"$overall_ok\\\"` (if equivalent behavior is preserved).\\n    10→- [ ] 9. Revalidate step sequencing for each agent so `RUN_<STEP>` logic, `--fail-fast`, and `help` path still behave identically after helper refactor.\\n    11→- [ ] 10. Run targeted checks: `tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh npm-agent`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh terra-agent`, and focused shellcheck on the three edited scripts.\\n    12→- [ ] 11. Verify measurable file size reduction versus pre-edit baselines and confirm no helper behavior regressions from `setup_outdir`/`setup_lock` (especially lock contention and cleanup semantics).\\n    13→- [ ] 12. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\\n    14→- [ ] 13. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\\n    15→\\n    16→## Architecture Review\\n    17→\\n    18→### System Boundaries\\n    19→\\n    20→The runtime is split into three layers.\\n    21→\\n    22→1) Shared runtime layer in `lib/x-agent-common.sh` holds boilerplate that is structurally identical across agents: output helpers, environment defaults, tool checks, output-dir lifecycle, lock lifecycle, and final summary formatting.\\n    23→\\n    24→2) Domain runner layer in `skills/<agent>/scripts/<agent>-agent.sh` holds project-specific logic only: command dispatch, tool arguments, package/tool-specific step functions, and domain-specific error messaging.\\n    25→\\n    26→3) Test/packaging layer in `tests/run-scenarios.sh` and `install.sh` exercises contract and distribution.\\n    27→\\n    28→`tests/run-scenarios.sh` is a strict integration boundary because all behavior claims are verified by the fixture contract, not by unit tests.\\n    29→\\n    30→### Dependency Graph and Coupling\\n    31→\\n    32→- Hard dependency: each edited script depends on `lib/x-agent-common.sh` at runtime.\\n    33→- Direct coupling path: `SCRIPT_DIR -> ../../../lib -> lib/x-agent-common.sh` (fragile if scripts are relocated).\\n    34→- Shared optional dependencies: `flock`, `perl`, `bash`, and command-line tools per agent.\\n    35→- Packaging coupling: `install.sh` must ensure `lib/` is installed in both local and remote modes.\\n    36→\\n    37→The explicit coupling is acceptable for this phase but should be tracked because path-coupling is the highest single fragility point.\\n    38→\\n    39→### Data Flow Patterns and Bottlenecks\\n    40→\\n    41→1) Input/env processing: args and knobs are resolved first (`RUN_*`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `MAX_LINES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`).\\n    42→2) Setup phase: create `OUTDIR`, install exit trap via `setup_outdir`, acquire lock via `setup_lock`.\\n    43→3) Execution phase: run ordered steps, each writing command output to `$OUTDIR/<step>.log` and printing truncated diagnostics + elapsed time.\\n    44→4) Aggregation: update `overall_ok`, optionally short-circuit with `should_continue`.\\n    45→5) Summary phase: call `print_overall \\\"$overall_ok\\\"`, then return exit code.\\n    46→\\n    47→Primary bottlenecks remain external tool execution (`cargo`, `node`, `terraform`), not shell orchestration.\\n    48→\\n    49→### Security Architecture\\n    50→\\n    51→- Input vectors are local shell arguments and environment variables.\\n    52→- Risk surface is command execution from user workspace; current pattern is command-injection-prone only if shell variables are interpolated unsafely. Existing scripts already pass this through unquoted args in places requiring shell parsing, so security posture is mostly inherited and must remain unchanged.\\n    53→- Lock files are local and only advisory. Existing fallback to perl ensures compatibility but does not provide cryptographic guarantees.\\n    54→- `install.sh` path rewriting and symlink/copy behavior should remain unchanged to avoid path injection from remote fetches; this phase only inherits those mechanics.\\n    55→\\n    56→### Architectural Decision Options\\n    57→\\n    58→1) Option A: Keep only hardcoded source path `../../../lib` and no abstraction.\\n    59→Why: aligns with FR-2 requirement text and current install layout. Lowest code churn.\\n    60→Cost/Risk: tight coupling to script location and difficult future portability.\\n    61→Impact: fastest path, minimal change footprint.\\n    62→\\n    63→2) Option B: Introduce `resolve_lib_dir()` in `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\\n    64→Why: centralizes path logic and reduces relocation risk.\\n    65→Cost/Risk: deviates from explicit required snippet, may require additional behavior changes and tests now.\\n    66→Impact: better future flexibility, higher refactor risk for this phase.\\n    67→\\n    68→3) Option C: Add per-agent `LIB_DIR` override env fallback (e.g., `RA_LAUNCHER_LIB_DIR`).\\n    69→Why: allows tests or installs to override without path math in scripts.\\n    70→Cost/Risk: extra configuration surface and allowed-tools complexity.\\n    71→Impact: flexibility increase, but overkill for this narrow spec.\\n    72→\\n    73→Recommended: Option A for this phase because it matches explicit spec requirement and previous extraction assumptions, with a follow-up ticket for optional Option B once all agents are stable.\\n    74→\\n    75→### Implications for Future Specs\\n    76→\\n    77→- All future agent work should preserve helper boundary and call pattern for consistency.\\n    78→- Future specs can de-duplicate path coupling by upgrading the shared lib to Option B after this phase.\\n    79→- Any new agent should be validated against the same `run-scenarios` contract before introducing more helpers in the shared layer.\\n    80→\\n    81→## Code Quality Planning\\n    82→\\n    83→### Module Organization\\n    84→\\n    85→The goal is a clean separation between shared runtime helpers and domain step implementations.\\n    86→\\n    87→1. Keep `lib/x-agent-common.sh` as a pure helper module with no side effects on source.\\n    88→2. Keep agent scripts minimal and domain-centric: parser, run_* functions, and dispatch only.\\n    89→3. Keep all `CHANGE` behaviors (`CHANGED_FILES`) in domain scripts because semantics differ by tool.\\n    90→\\n    91→### DRY Opportunities\\n    92→\\n    93→Most duplication is exactly the boilerplate block, not business logic.\\n    94→\\n    95→- Remove repeated block variables and helper functions from all three scripts.\\n    96→- Reuse `setup_outdir` and `setup_lock` exactly once in each script.\\n    97→- Keep helper calls like `print_overall` only where identical to avoid introducing non-equivalent wrappers.\\n    98→\\n    99→### Error Handlin","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false,"persistedOutputPath":"/Users/chrisraethke/.claude/projects/-Users-chrisraethke-projects-x-agent/6009da08-f492-4e44-8ec1-e3891bd2efc5/tool-results/bj3r85k1h.txt","persistedOutputSize":74758}}
